WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Okay, as a first move, you're saying something like "différance," or in this case "iteration,"

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:37.000
is the origin, right? But as origin, that thing doesn't function like an origin anymore.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
So that would be the second, the second step would be the second thing.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.000
And, you know, like, I don't understand, I mean, honestly, to me, when I reread the Searle response,

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:52.000
I don't understand, this strikes me as actually a fairly straightforward point, right?

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.000
The idea of the basic characteristic of writing is iterability, right?

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
It's capacity to go from one place to the next.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:09.000
Now, where Derrida goes with that is one of the consequences is that that means that the mark is never self-identical.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.000
That, I can see people being like, wait, hold on a second, like, I don't necessarily get that consequence, right?

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Like, but I don't understand why Searle has such difficulty understanding the notion of iterability, right?

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Like, that anything, the basic characteristic, and it's really clear in his response, like, he just doesn't, he just doesn't seem to get that.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:39.000
He doesn't seem to get that, like, you know, because he makes the argument, he's like, look, there are plenty of situations in which people write something to one another.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Like, he gives the example of a grocery store note, like, you write a grocery store list, and Derrida is, you know, is like, but that's a perfect example of the nonsense.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Like, of course people can be present, the other can be present when you're writing, but for writing to work, it has to be possible for them not to be.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:04.000
It's fascinating because that's the exact, like, critique that Nate was just describing with that third reviewer.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Like, to say, like, look, like, there is a structural, like, structurally, you know, like, we are all set up to participate in X.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Now, that doesn't mean that everyone is equally activating X at all times, or certainly not intending to, but that is a factor that is constantly there as a, you know, either as a more or less latent possibility, but always activated to some degree or another.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:37.000
It's the same thing here, it's just like, you don't have to be absent from your writing, you just have to be able to be absent from the writing.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Well, and the fact that absence is constitutive in Derrida's case, I mean, it is a little bit, like, that is kind of a scary concept if you're invested in a metaphysics of presence or of self-presence, right?

00:02:50.000 --> 00:03:00.000
I mean, it's like, if we're all activated by some sort of weird abyss or absence of self at all times, that makes everything ephemeral, right?

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
I mean, self-identity, cultural identity.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:11.000
I mean, not ephemeral, because that's where, like, I don't, I don't follow on that one, like, because for me, it's not ephemeral, it's just iterative.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Yeah.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Like, it's, so that's, that's where it's important is that, like, iteration isn't absence, you know, absence actually would be just sort of reassuring, right?

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
It would just, well, it happens to not be there, right?

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Yeah.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:31.000
It's like, it's, it's, it actually is to me, it's, you know, like, what makes these marks work this way is context.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Yeah.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Which, by the way, is also made up of marks.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Right.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Right.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Right.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Like, iterated marks.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
That just strikes me as, like, okay, here's what convention is.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:48.000
When we say, like, here's a conventional way that we are, to understand one another, to have this conversation, we are relying on a whole series of conventions.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
But the conventions don't come from God.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Yeah.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Right.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
But I think you're coming at it from an already pretty sophisticated understanding of the conceptual terrain.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Like, for someone like Searle, or somebody just not, you know, knowledgeable of deconstruction, like, there's no firmness of the foundation, at least apparently, right, to this concept of iterability, right?

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Like, yes, iterability, you know, instantiates convention, which instantiates self, or whatever.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.000
But, like, that's still pretty precarious, as opposed to, like, the God foundation, or, like, selfness.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
But, like, self's not a God guy, right?

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:28.000
No.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Like, I mean, and most of those folks are not.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Like, they're not, they don't believe in the transcendent dropping down.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
They just don't, it's the Nietzschean critique of the madman.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
They just don't follow out the consequences, right?

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Right.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:40.000
They're not pursuing that.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Well, even Austin.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Well, they don't, they can't accept the madness to take a hold of them.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
I mean, like, you read all of that philosophy of language stuff.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Like, everything from, like, well, not, like, earlier Wittgenstein, you know, all the way up through Searle.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And it's like, look, we're going to approach this thing, but we have to have some kind of baseline to approach it from, and that thing is going to be some kind of, like, ordinary language.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.000
Right.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And then we're going to use ordinary language, and then we're going to use ordinary language to examine ordinary language.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Right.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.000
But it's very, very difficult to, like, keep an eye on the assumptions that you're operating with.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And, like, to me, I've never been, it's never been so clear to me as to how powerful the epigraph is in this, you know, still confining ourselves for simplicity to the spoken utterance.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Right.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:52.000
I mean, like, that is just, it just is profoundly redundant in the way that it tries to assert the obviousness of a primacy of speech overriding, for a simplicity over complexity, for the capacity of thinking sort of like the safe, normal area that we can confine ourselves to, and then go to the extraneous material.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Without realizing that, like, you know, the ordinary is not safe, the ordinary is not stable, none of this kind of stuff, there's no safe starting point to be able to build out there.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:16.820
Well, this is, and honestly, yeah, and for me, in the lecture, I felt like the most interesting part for me in thinking through it was exactly that point where I said, like, look, here's Searle's defense of Austin.

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:27.740
He's saying, Austin's not getting rid of jokes and plays and lies, he's just saying, in a fairly obvious way, that if you're going to understand speaking, you don't want to start with those.

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:31.320
And my reaction to that is, yeah, that makes sense, right?

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:32.620
That seems reasonable.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:41.620
It's, like, there is that way in which that claim is like, yeah, if you're going to understand speaking, you don't start with actors on a stage, you don't start with people making jokes or telling lies, right?

00:06:41.760 --> 00:06:42.560
I get that.

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:49.240
And what Derrida is saying is, the fact that it sort of seems reasonable to you, that's the problem, right?

00:06:49.740 --> 00:06:52.840
Like, that's exactly, like, because it does, it does seem reasonable to me.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:07:03.400
It seems like, okay, it's methodologically, like, it would never cross my mind for a moment to say that's a ridiculous presupposition until I read Derrida and go, wait, hold on.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:12.060
You're saying, implicitly, you're saying that jokes and lies are less ordinary than direct, you know, honest locution.

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:14.120
It's like, that just seems ridiculous, right?

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:24.160
Like, they're all equally ordinary, so starting at one place, you know, is going to skew the way that you, the way you treat those things.

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:30.480
But most importantly, it points out to me, like, that was the interesting part for me on terms of the, like, the turn to affect, right?

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:32.240
Is that don't trust your gut.

00:07:32.780 --> 00:07:33.480
Yeah, that's a good point.

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:39.060
Like, that's the conclusion, the conclusion for me was like, hey, this seems intuitively and at a gut level a reasonable decision.

00:07:39.300 --> 00:07:46.060
But what that shows you is that your intuition in your gut is already constituted, you know, by those series of marks.

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:48.080
Yeah, and riven by context.

00:07:48.620 --> 00:08:05.580
You can see, like, I mean, like, the sort of, like, the intuition list sort of, like, I mean, again, this is, like, oddly part of, like, analytic philosophy who, you know, is, you know, eschews generally sort of, like, the theological, like, God just planted ideas in our head.

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:18.580
But yet they have no problem with going to sort of, like, what intuitively makes sense within normal discourse as some sort of, like, baseline test for, you know, figuring out where the real thinking happens or where the real problem happens.

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:24.340
And that's, like, you know, that's so closely knit to, like, the traditional idealism.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:25.940
It's like, you know, there are first ideas.

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:31.420
There are first ideas that, you know, just at that gut level you can't deny.

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:44.900
And, like, the possibility that those most baseline assumptions are constructed in some kind of way and that they're constructed differently for different people at different times is, like, I mean, I think this is going back to what Nate was saying.

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:57.960
It's, like, it's not that hard to intellectually follow that line of argumentation, but it's definitely hard to accept that because the consequences are so destabilizing if you feel like you need that, that stabilizing basis.

00:08:58.480 --> 00:08:58.920
Right.

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:08.840
Well, but another way of saying it, and I, I, I mean, we were, what we were talking about before is, like, I feel like there's no real strong sense of history in that kind of thinking.

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:09.280
Yeah.

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:11.700
Like, for this kind of thinking, I think there's a strong sense of history.

00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:18.680
Like, what gives it solidity to me is the fact that it's been iterated for fucking millennia, right?

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:21.660
Like, long pre-existing me, right?

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:30.500
And so, this, so, for instance, like, this interaction is an accretion of millennia of interactions of, of all kinds.

00:09:30.580 --> 00:09:35.980
And I'm, I don't know, I'm super comfortable with that idea, I guess, or maybe I'm too comfortable.

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:38.380
And I think for a lot of people, it's like, no, no, no, no, no, no.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:42.380
This, this is its own thing, and we can rely on that.

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:49.220
But, for me, the lesson of, like, don't trust your gut and don't trust your intuition is to say those, that intuition has been built, right?

00:09:49.220 --> 00:09:49.360
Yeah.

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:51.880
It has, it has been made up over time.

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:56.300
Now, again, my lifetime was only, has only been 52 years, right?

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:59.480
Like, so, but it, it's, it's not just 52 years old.

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:06.540
And everything about me is made in the midst of, again, I just find that, that's solid.

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:08.500
I don't see that as unstable.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:22.380
And, and that's so often, though, the critique of some kind of constructivism or some kind of relativism that, you know, like, well, if there aren't sort of, like, first truths, foundations, stabilities, then anything can be everything at any time.

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:22.960
It's like, well.

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:24.200
No, no, it can't.

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:26.620
Two out of those three are, are true.

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:31.500
Anything can be everything, but only having gone through the work.

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:41.580
And sometimes that work doesn't, it doesn't take very long or very much work, and some of that stuff would take millennia and, you know, like, enormous amounts of labor and whatever else, right?

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:44.860
It's like, but to your point, it's like, look, the earth is not solid.

00:10:45.120 --> 00:10:46.560
Continents are drifting, right?

00:10:46.720 --> 00:10:48.300
We're flying in space.

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:49.900
The sun's not lasting forever.

00:10:49.900 --> 00:11:04.580
But it has enough inertia and enough stability for me to, for, well, not just me to carve out a pretty stable life, but an entire, like, you know, several millions of years of species to, like, evolve and die out and mutate.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:06.280
You know, like, it's stable enough.

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:16.400
That's where the comfort and discomfort comes in, because I feel like John and maybe all of us are fairly comfortable with a radicalized notion of context and contingency.

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:22.160
And you can confront that and still, like, you know, assemble yourself and your scholarship after that.

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:27.400
For people like Searle and Austin even, like, they're trying to build taxonomies.

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:36.840
And that, a radicalized notion of context or contingency disrupts and destabilizes those taxonomies to the point where they don't function.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:45.060
So, like, they're, that thinking context in the way that we're trying to do, like, doesn't enable those.

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:46.080
But it can still function.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:55.160
Like, you can still, I mean, the point of the radical contingency would be there would be no invalid reason for a taxonomy either, right?

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:57.820
That's where the next two, the next two lectures are on critique.

00:11:57.980 --> 00:12:03.380
Like, what is the basis for critique when you have this kind of, what I'm calling, like, a flat ontology?

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:04.080
Right.

00:12:04.120 --> 00:12:15.360
So, you know, and, and, I mean, that to me is actually, like, the reason that we're, the reason that they're concerned with it is I think that you actually lose the basis for critique as being,

00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:19.280
being able to say it's attributable to some fault in the thing.

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:24.840
Like, all you can, all you can say is it's not me or it's not, you know, that's all you can really say.

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:38.000
And I found that, like, that's a much more interesting pluralist direction to me is, as opposed to saying you're wrong, meaning your thing doesn't cohere with the state of affairs, right?

00:12:38.060 --> 00:12:47.740
Like, there, you have to come up with other ways of thinking critique and it just, it just shows, like, the extent to which some fundamental notion of truth is so fucking powerful.

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:59.100
Like, even the people who are not invested in a big metaphysical godlike idea of it are still committed, you know, to that, like, I have to be able to tell someone they're wrong, right?

00:12:59.180 --> 00:12:59.500
You know?

00:12:59.700 --> 00:12:59.980
Right.

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:03.420
Or I have to believe that I'm right would be the flip side of it, right?

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:04.060
Like, either one.

00:13:04.100 --> 00:13:05.420
It doesn't matter which one you choose.

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:17.700
But it's like, no, yours is an intervention into the world, again, based on a whole series, like, an accreted series of ways of looking at things that can do lots of, like, speech act theory can do lots of interesting and useful work,

00:13:17.920 --> 00:13:24.640
regardless of whether or not its premises are, like, that Austin doesn't follow out the general theory, right?

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:28.820
Though, I've got to say, you know, it's such a difference for me between Searle and Austin.

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:34.780
It's precisely Austin's willingness to follow that line of thinking.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.020
You know, like, what's that line?

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:45.500
I think maybe Derrida cites it, the, you know, isn't it exhilarating to feel the firm grip of a foundation slipping beneath our feet?

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:54.160
Like, you know, as he's trying to build this taxonomy and, you know, the taxonomy itself is showing him holes or contradictions or whatever else,

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:58.440
he's got to, like, all right, chuck this one over my shoulder and let's try another one.

00:13:58.500 --> 00:14:01.340
And, you know, he has a very sort of iterative approach.

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:06.100
And, you know, that's, like, I mean, to me, that's incredibly admirable.

00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:12.760
And, you know, like, he goes from, he really, he does, like, very experimentally kind of go from,

00:14:13.060 --> 00:14:19.560
hmm, there is this sort of, like, odd, peculiar form of speech that doesn't mean things.

00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:20.940
You know, it does things.

00:14:20.980 --> 00:14:22.080
Let's call it the performative.

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:23.680
Now, let's figure out how they work.

00:14:23.940 --> 00:14:32.760
Oh, as I sort of, like, figure out section four sub point three C, you know, I realize, shit, all, everything is a performative,

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:41.920
even though it's supposedly constitutive utterances, like, have, you know, a performative dimension to them as the, like, that I think or I declare or I posits.

00:14:42.540 --> 00:14:45.360
And, you know, then suddenly he's willing to follow it through.

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:47.340
And it's, like, it's slow and it's meticulous.

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:50.940
And, you know, like, in some ways you're, like, you know, I'm going to speed you up, JL.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:57.440
But it's certainly, you know, he doesn't seem like, he's certainly not stubborn.

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:05.320
But why the recovery and possibly even privileging of the Constative in Austin?

00:15:05.580 --> 00:15:09.040
Like, why doesn't Austin get to Derrida?

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:14.240
Like, at least from Derrida's perspective, like, he's still kind of attributing a failure to Austin.

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:15.400
He might not say that.

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:17.360
He will not go to the general theory.

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:17.900
Right.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:19.480
Like, he can't.

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:20.720
I mean, that's Derrida's claim.

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:23.540
What disenables him from doing that, you know?

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:25.640
Like, he didn't write lecture 11.

00:15:25.900 --> 00:15:26.340
I don't know.

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:27.900
No, no, no.

00:15:27.900 --> 00:15:28.540
I don't think it's that.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:30.440
Because that's another interesting thing.

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:37.320
I mean, in rereading How to Do Things with Words again, he abandons the performative constitutive by about lecture 9 or 10.

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:39.380
He's like, those categories just don't work.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:41.640
And that's where illocutionary, perlocutionary, you know.

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:44.760
And I don't think it's just that he didn't figure it out.

00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:45.260
I do.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:50.480
I think that Derrida's right in a sense of, like, he puts off till later this question of the general theory.

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:52.840
