00:15:57.860 --> 00:15:59.340
That's a constitutive possibility.

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:01.580
Now, why doesn't it, right?

00:16:01.660 --> 00:16:05.120
Is then the next, like, everything doesn't go everywhere all of the time.

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:14.600
And so thinking of a logic of convention or context or whatever, so that's just a different project than the one that he set himself out on, right?

00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:15.740
Like, that's my take.

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:19.740
But, again, he's totally fine changing that project, right?

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:26.440
Like, I mean, you know, I mean, like, look, I think you're right, again, that there's a certain fear.

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:32.160
There's a certain, like, if anything can go everywhere all the time, you know, at least from this perspective, that's scary.

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:35.880
Don't follow that through and see where it takes me.

00:16:36.260 --> 00:16:38.760
But he's all, and I think that shows itself the most.

00:16:38.860 --> 00:17:00.300
And, again, his sort of, like, assumption that, all right, well, if I'm going to abandon, you know, the language of the true false, at least at the level of the performative or elocutionary, which is going to kind of become everything, then, you know, I've got to figure out a different term that, that, what's the word I'm looking for?

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:17.840
Right, but I mean, like, I think Derrida's answer to that is, well, he does all of those things, and that's what's interesting about it, but he's still committed to the horizon of consciousness as being the baseline.

00:17:18.260 --> 00:17:28.260
Like, it's going to all, you know, yes, it is not the transmission of a preexisting idea, as it is in most versions of communication, but it is still about felicity and felicity.

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:29.600
What makes something felicitous?

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:37.100
Well, it's because I wanted to accomplish, like, you know, the way that we, the way that I just narrated the situation with the teaching award, right?

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:42.880
Like, it's like, okay, I had an intention and attempted to manage things in a particular direction, right?

00:17:42.940 --> 00:17:44.100
Like, that's the first thing.

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:53.600
So, in other words, there's a wall, there's a barrier that he's like, look, the sort of, the communicative apparatus can go all wonky, but it's always sort of subordinated to the intention.

00:17:53.680 --> 00:18:02.080
Yeah, which is what keeps it from going, you know, if consciousness was wonky, then language would be more, like, would be wonkier.

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:13.180
But that's, that's the fear, that's, that's where I'm saying, I don't feel like, if you say consciousness is non-self-present, I just don't feel like you, I don't feel like you lose anything.

00:18:13.180 --> 00:18:14.940
Anything, right?

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:17.560
Like, I understand that people feel like you lose everything.

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:19.280
But I don't, I don't get that.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:22.020
That used to, that was a thought that terrified me as an undergrad.

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:35.280
Because, you know, because I was always the most pulled by philosophies of the mind, philosophies of, like, the self, like the constitution of the consciousness or soul or whatever, whether it was Plato or Descartes or whoever.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:48.800
And, like, that, like, I mean, it was in some ways, like, a driving force, like, I don't care what it looks like, it can be, you know, different than I would imagine it, but I have to be able to have some kind of stabilizing sense.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:50.960
I don't even know what stability looks like right now.

00:18:51.340 --> 00:18:57.320
And when I look back on that now, I can remember how it felt, but I don't remember why it felt that way.

00:18:57.480 --> 00:18:58.860
I don't remember, like.

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:00.500
Yeah.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:09.120
Yeah, I remember, yeah, I remember that feeling being a little more daunting or, you know, scary, even just a few years ago.

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:20.640
Like, the notion that you're not self-directed, like, or that there's too many contingencies to fully account for the direction of yourself, your intentions, your motivations, et cetera.

00:19:20.780 --> 00:19:33.040
But then, like you're saying, John, I mean, it's like, it's not like that situation in itself is scary, first of all, because, as Derek was arguing, it's just an ontological fact.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:33.880
It's just the case.

00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:34.420
Right, right.

00:19:34.420 --> 00:19:36.680
So it's like, it's not like you can battle against that.

00:19:37.100 --> 00:19:41.360
Well, lots of things are scary that are the case, like lions and tigers and death, right?

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:42.960
It bears, right, right.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:43.340
Yeah.

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:50.820
But it's interesting there, because, I mean, in a certain sense, there's a definition of consciousness built in there, which is the anxiety about its not being in the center.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:56.480
Like, what consciousness is, is an anxiety of its sort of non-control.

00:19:56.660 --> 00:20:04.320
Because, in many ways, we're saying, just be more materialist about this and really think of consciousness as a material, as a material phenomenon.

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:04.920
As a machine.

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:05.220
Right?

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:13.260
Like, yeah, and it's like, at least to me, honestly, for me, that idea or that thinking is so fucking liberating.

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:16.720
Like, it's just like, oh, I don't have absolute responsibility.

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:18.260
I don't have total control.

00:20:18.380 --> 00:20:19.600
I don't have total awareness.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:21.540
Like, I can't have any of those things.

00:20:21.880 --> 00:20:24.320
And so I can be a lot less neurotic.

00:20:24.400 --> 00:20:25.700
That doesn't mean don't pay attention.

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:28.120
It doesn't mean just, like, take things as they come.

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:32.720
It can just mean you intervene the way that you intervene and things go as they go.

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:33.780
Right.

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:36.340
Well, that's the other fear, right?

00:20:36.380 --> 00:20:40.100
Not just the sort of the I'm not in control or the anxiety of not being in the center.

00:20:40.320 --> 00:20:45.640
But the sort of, like, I mean, as another stabilizing mechanism of, you know, the moralization of action.

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:52.920
That, you know, I, you know, if I'm not stable or self-present, then I can't be guilty or, you know, laudable for, you know, my actions.

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:54.380
That's the neutral line, right?

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:56.300
And neither can anyone else.

00:20:56.400 --> 00:20:58.460
And then if that happens, then it's all chaos.

00:20:58.560 --> 00:21:09.900
And it's always interesting that it's like, you know, it can't be the case because I don't have, yeah, I don't have the capacity to, you know, I will go back to critique to say, you're wrong, I'm right.

00:21:10.020 --> 00:21:13.060
Or I'm even, or even I'm wrong and you're right, right?

00:21:13.060 --> 00:21:15.320
Because there's a certain, like, comfort in that.

00:21:16.220 --> 00:21:21.340
You know, even when it's a bad outcome, at least I know where I'm at in relationship to the thing.

00:21:21.460 --> 00:21:28.220
What's a little strange about this essay is that most of the stuff that we're talking about, we're extending the implications.

00:21:29.080 --> 00:21:31.520
We haven't talked, we haven't even talked about the essay.

00:21:31.720 --> 00:21:40.300
But what I'm, but I mean, it's like, the, all of these things are kind of loaded into Derrida's thinking, but they're not explicitly articulated in this essay.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:48.200
He's talking about, like, the sort of details of speech acts and writings.

00:21:48.860 --> 00:21:59.180
And he's not getting, he's not even really hinting at the ethical implications or about the anxiety, the potential anxiety of a metaphysics of presence and being invested in that.

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:14.680
And I actually think it might have been useful to at least point towards some of that stuff because that's almost necessary to think through some of the consequences that he's saying Searle refuses to admit or that Austin kind of refuses to acknowledge.

00:22:14.680 --> 00:22:23.560
Because, like, a lot of that anxiety regarding the loss of self-presence, that's almost like a structural component of this thing.

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:26.360
And I don't feel like we get a lot of that in SEC.

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:27.680
Like, it's just...

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:29.880
That's a more existentialist...

00:22:29.880 --> 00:22:38.560
Right, right, but I'm saying, like, even just, like, a paragraph, like, would have kind of elucidated some of these points that we're talking through.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:41.420
It would have made, at least for me, I'm just being selfish here.

00:22:41.420 --> 00:22:46.340
It would have made the essay more, given it more import for my thinking.

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:47.640
You know what I'm saying?

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:59.420
I mean, I see, like, his point of departure isn't so much, like, isn't it fascinating that no one is able to, you know, like, contravene or sort of, like, think through the...

00:22:59.880 --> 00:23:02.740
The supposed obviousness of all of these assumptions.

00:23:02.860 --> 00:23:03.900
Like, that's not a starting point.

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:07.000
It's like, look, everyone thinks this is just so obviously the case.

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:09.040
I'm going to demonstrate how it's impossible.

00:23:09.840 --> 00:23:16.280
And, you know, I mean, like, you know, that's a launch of what, in many ways, is a pretty straightforward critique.

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:19.540
I mean, I think in many ways a generous critique, but it is a critique.

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:28.120
There isn't then the second move to then say, and why in the world are we all so self-assured of this thing, right?

00:23:28.180 --> 00:23:30.880
And that would turn toward the existential conversation.

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:40.860
I mean, I can imagine, I don't know anything about the composition of this thing, but I can imagine, like, at some point people were like, oh, man, this performativity thing, this is really cool.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:41.980
Like, you should check this out.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.720
This is really smart versions of language.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:47.420
And he read it, and he was like, eh, it's not all that, right?

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:49.160
Like, it's still privileging consciousness.

00:23:49.160 --> 00:23:56.300
And then he built the whole context argument, you know, the front end of the context is like, I'm giving a paper.

00:23:56.540 --> 00:24:02.760
So, you know, the whole communication stuff was like, hey, here's how we can reduce the meaning of the word communication at the context.

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:04.420
There isn't a notion of context.

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:09.160
Like, the whole thing seems to me to sort of lead towards what he basically, I mean, it is.

00:24:09.220 --> 00:24:18.040
And it's a critique, and that's the beef I have with this essay, is that I believe very much that one could read Austin quite differently.

00:24:18.420 --> 00:24:24.840
And one could do the critique move on Austin and then show Austin pushing through that move, right?

00:24:24.840 --> 00:24:26.860
Like, I do think that that's the case.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:33.420
So, Austin retains a privileging of consciousness, but only if you stop at, like, lecture 10, right?

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:34.800
Like, or 11, right?

00:24:34.840 --> 00:24:44.460
Like, I mean, you could, the category of the elocutionary, again, he does remain oddly beholden to a pretty conventional notion of Austin's intention.

00:24:45.340 --> 00:24:46.320
I mean, he does.

00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:49.620
Like, even his response to Searle.

00:24:51.040 --> 00:25:01.660
And that's, to me, that's the point at which, like, I find myself, I always, every time I read it, I just have this kind of bristling response to those moments where I'm like, he didn't have to go there.

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:02.600
He didn't have to do that.

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:03.340
Again, whatever.

00:25:03.500 --> 00:25:05.180
It's not like, so he's not me.

00:25:05.360 --> 00:25:07.060
That's all I'm really saying.

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:08.700
And that's okay.

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:14.120
And I've got to say, like, you know, you have to wonder what kind of, you don't have to wonder.

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:15.540
It's actually really obvious.

00:25:15.540 --> 00:25:35.520
Like, running this through the framework of a critique allows, like, allows this to be read and understood and disseminated and gained traction in ways that what you're suggesting, which I think I agree would be more interesting, but the number of people that would be able to follow through it, I mean, like, this is not exactly an accessible essay, right?

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:40.380
So he's already, you know, speaking to a pretty small percentage of people.

00:25:40.900 --> 00:25:45.660
And then to make the move that you're suggesting would shrink that, I think, even more.

00:25:45.780 --> 00:25:51.720
I mean, you know, there's a reason why, you know, for every person that knows Deleuze, three people know Derrida.

00:25:52.380 --> 00:26:01.420
I mean, and think about Deleuze's, like, the critiques of Deleuze's historical figures is, I love those readings.

00:26:01.540 --> 00:26:12.080
And I can never read, you know, Kant or Hume or, I mean, Spinoza or any of those others, like, with, like, they've been so thoroughly, well, penetrated by.

00:26:12.260 --> 00:26:12.700
Deleuzified.

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:14.360
Deleuzified, right?

00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:16.880
That, you know, I can't read, I think they're phenomenal.

00:26:17.360 --> 00:26:21.600
But very few people think that they are sort of, like, well, that's not Kant.

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:23.260
It's like, it is now.

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:29.680
Someone, you know, like, anything can be everything, and Deleuze did the work to make Kant that, right?

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:34.600
Like, I can't, I don't know what it would be like to live in a world where Kant isn't that anymore.

00:26:35.240 --> 00:26:43.860
And let's not underestimate it, and this is something I'd give just a passing nod to in the lecture, but we wouldn't know Derrida, right?

00:26:43.860 --> 00:26:57.780
Like, if, the function of critique, right, allowed, was one of the things that I think allowed him, and it's those moments, the moments that I bristle at, there's those moments that allowed him to be like, here's deconstruction, right?

00:26:57.980 --> 00:27:10.660
And sort of produce it as an international, I mean, not only that, there are many other things, but nevertheless, that kind of institutional recognition that allows us to have this conversation today, right?

00:27:10.660 --> 00:27:16.640
Was, because he's saying, I am not Searle, or Austin, or ordinary language philosophy.

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:26.460
John, he is just taking a deep breath, and then saying, I'm going to do my quantitative analysis very briefly, and then move on.

00:27:27.060 --> 00:27:27.960
Yeah, yeah.

00:27:28.520 --> 00:27:29.400
He made the decision.

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:31.180
But you're right.

00:27:31.300 --> 00:27:32.100
I mean, he is.

00:27:32.220 --> 00:27:34.120
That's the move that he makes there.

00:27:34.460 --> 00:27:37.640
Now, again, this is where the critique thing comes in later.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:48.880
Like, he has, you know, in terms of the beef that he has with Searle, again, I'm of two minds, because on the one hand, I'm sympathetic, having heard similar kinds of things from various people in response to my stuff.

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:54.740
Like, I get, I understand that you get to a point where you're just like, I am so fucking tired of this, I'm going to eviscerate it.

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:57.160
Like, I totally get that.

00:27:57.240 --> 00:28:01.440
At the same time, it is premised on this idea that Searle misunderstood me.

00:28:02.540 --> 00:28:07.680
And so he, and it's like, so again, he's going to say, I'm not relying on the self-identity of meaning.

00:28:07.820 --> 00:28:09.060
There isn't just one me here.

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:16.280
But I am going to rely on this notion of the norms, the conventional norms of reading that Searle is either not capable of.

00:28:16.360 --> 00:28:19.120
So there's, you know, an implicit sort of arrogance to it.

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:22.180
Again, institutionally, that functions really well.

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:23.580
That makes Derrida recognizable.

00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:25.700
It creates all kinds of, you know.

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:31.200
And that's also why SEC is, it circulates more widely and is better known than Limited Inc.

00:28:31.500 --> 00:28:36.740
Because, I mean, largely because, you know, you're right, he still does a lot of that.

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:42.500
But he's also so careful to try to circumscribe, or not circumscribe, circumvent you from saying that.

00:28:42.500 --> 00:28:47.220
Because he's like, who, like, was I misunderstood?

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:48.720
If so, by whom?

00:28:48.860 --> 00:28:51.780
And then, you know, like, then Searle isn't simply Searle.

00:28:51.900 --> 00:28:54.380
He becomes, you know, Searle Limited Inc., right?

00:28:54.800 --> 00:28:55.240
That's right.

00:28:55.480 --> 00:29:00.380
So, you know, like, the question, like, on one hand, he's like, you fucking idiot, you misunderstood me.

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:06.220
But in every single move of saying that, he complicates, wait, what, who misunderstood me?

00:29:06.380 --> 00:29:06.740
How?

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:08.300
What would misremembering?

00:29:08.360 --> 00:29:08.940
What would be me?

00:29:09.060 --> 00:29:09.220
Right?

00:29:09.300 --> 00:29:10.980
And so he's constantly undermining.

00:29:11.980 --> 00:29:17.980
You know, and talking about therapy right here, like, you know, imagine, like, you know, Derrida has that desire to eviscerate you.

00:29:18.060 --> 00:29:20.960
You just didn't understand me at all.

00:29:21.100 --> 00:29:23.280
And you didn't care to even try.

00:29:23.540 --> 00:29:24.820
I'm going to eviscerate you.

00:29:25.060 --> 00:29:34.340
And then I'm going to turn my desire to eviscerate you and the very mechanisms by which I'm going to eviscerate you into a line of thinking.

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:36.520
And let it undo itself.

00:29:37.140 --> 00:29:40.680
That's actually, I have got a lot of admiration for that.

00:29:41.160 --> 00:29:44.040
You know, when you think about him being that fucking pissed off at a moment.

00:29:44.380 --> 00:29:44.500
Yeah.

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:52.280
It's a lot of tension, though, and kind of like a, even a contradiction at the heart of the project, then, in that case.

00:29:52.280 --> 00:30:02.100
Because deconstruction, in sort of a semi-vulgar sense, as we're talking, is like a marketing enterprise, where he's like, it's almost just critique it in that sense.

00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:10.360
But deconstruction, at its most rigorous, is a thorough inhabitation of a text, even if he's still making those cutting gestures.

00:30:11.060 --> 00:30:15.440
He's not saying that his interlocutors, like Rousseau, are wrong.

00:30:16.080 --> 00:30:17.140
Like, he's rendering them.

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:17.820
Or even here.

00:30:18.100 --> 00:30:18.760
No, no, he's not.

00:30:18.820 --> 00:30:18.940
Yeah.

00:30:18.940 --> 00:30:23.740
And he's saying that they're symptomatic of a certain type of thinking.

00:30:24.180 --> 00:30:27.400
But that certainly doesn't, it means they're almost too correct.

00:30:27.860 --> 00:30:31.200
Like, Austin is so right that it makes him problematic.

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:37.920
But again, even to say that, that's not even as different of a claim as I think that you think that it is.

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:41.660
Because in that case, you're saying you're symptomatic of a way of thinking.

00:30:41.860 --> 00:30:43.920
You're saying that way of thinking is one thing.

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:45.180
It's called humanism.

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:46.680
It's called metaphysics or whatever.

00:30:47.260 --> 00:30:57.680
So even that move is still a kind of self-identifying move that, again, there are always marks and traces that allow a different way of doing that.

00:30:57.920 --> 00:31:03.240
Like, that's where you could do the, I mean, I have no problem with the critique move that he does on Austin.

00:31:03.360 --> 00:31:14.640
I just think it would have been a more interesting essay for me if, in addition to that, part three had been, Austin recognizes this and does other things differently later.

00:31:14.840 --> 00:31:15.040
Right?

00:31:15.140 --> 00:31:18.480
Like, in other words, turn Austin against Austin.

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:24.320
Instead of saying, Austin doesn't recognize the brilliance of his, yeah, yeah.

00:31:24.820 --> 00:31:25.000
Right.

00:31:25.220 --> 00:31:28.540
He doesn't, he doesn't, Austin's unable to get to iteration.

00:31:28.960 --> 00:31:31.860
It's like, but no, Austin, in other words, what's the problem?

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:35.520
Is he doesn't consciously recognize, right, iteration?

00:31:36.020 --> 00:31:37.040
I mean, that's the problem, right?

00:31:37.060 --> 00:31:40.380
And that's what Derrida will rely consistently on a notion of rigor.

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:41.280
Right?

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:42.900
It's not rigorous enough.

00:31:42.960 --> 00:31:47.080
And I'm like, well, what the fuck is rigor other than the horizon of conscious awareness?

00:31:47.920 --> 00:31:48.360
Yeah.

00:31:48.500 --> 00:31:48.700
Right?

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:56.640
And again, I'm totally, let me also say, I have learned so much from Derrida because of his commitment to that kind of rigor.

00:31:57.060 --> 00:32:02.200
And it's constituted me, so, you know, the idea of me critiquing it is itself kind of ridiculous.

00:32:02.200 --> 00:32:06.200
But I do have those, every time I read this, I have these moments of like, ugh.

00:32:07.160 --> 00:32:10.560
This is why we need cranky John swag for the podcast.

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:15.220
Like, even Derrida gets it.

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:24.740
Deleuze, Hegel, obviously, Heidegger, and, yeah, there needs to, yeah, there's cranky John, merch.

00:32:25.220 --> 00:32:25.400
Yeah.

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:36.020
But again, this is a really complicated, problematic, because it's like, how do you make it, I mean, maybe the question is like, how do you not make an intervention?

00:32:36.440 --> 00:32:41.740
Or like, how do you make an intervention that doesn't negate in any way?

00:32:41.740 --> 00:32:42.240
Becoming indiscernible.

00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:43.020
Right, right.

00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:44.580
Becoming indistinguishable in Deleuze.

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:45.040
Like, yeah.

00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:45.680
Right.

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:58.100
Well, so, I had a thought along those lines, just, you know, thinking about, you were talking about, like, how he uses critique to, in many ways, undo critique, right?

00:32:58.180 --> 00:33:01.160
So, I mean, like, in one way you could read that is, like, using the master's tools.

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:07.660
But in this case, he's like, showing how the master's tools don't even do what the master thinks that they do.

00:33:07.740 --> 00:33:15.360
And then, you know, like, when you're talking about how, like, for you, it would be more interesting if he didn't make those moves, or if he brought them full circle a little bit.

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:18.380
Is he just making a joke out of critique?

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:19.680
Yeah, I mean.

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:22.880
Is he mobilizing critique to make fun of?

00:33:22.940 --> 00:33:33.180
I mean, to, well, not make fun of critique, but to bring a certain kind of, if you follow through on his argument, you know, on, if you follow his line of thinking,

00:33:33.880 --> 00:33:37.460
then what he is, his so-called critique can't be a critique.

00:33:37.940 --> 00:33:40.240
And he had to have known it all the way, you know.

00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:42.500
But, okay.

00:33:42.820 --> 00:33:46.660
It was doing to Derrida what you were hoping Derrida was doing to Austin.

00:33:46.660 --> 00:33:47.560
Doing to Austin, yeah.

00:33:47.960 --> 00:33:50.060
So, that would be a next kind of move.

00:33:50.180 --> 00:33:59.920
I also do think that there's a reason for thinking that those moves serially, like what we were talking about at the very beginning of, like, you know, the first move is saying difference is an origin.

00:34:00.100 --> 00:34:05.640
And then the next move is saying the nature of difference means that it can't function as an origin.

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:08.500
Like, it problematizes the whole function of an origin.

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:15.800
And I think that the serial making of those points, and I actually take that to be a pretty Derridian point, right?

00:34:15.880 --> 00:34:23.040
Like, you know, the importance of that seriality, like to hook into one point in order to then unhook that point.

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:28.740
You know, whereas I feel like what I get from Deleuze is just, like, there are no origins.

00:34:29.220 --> 00:34:29.460
Yeah.

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:31.040
You know.

00:34:31.100 --> 00:34:31.200
Yeah.

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:33.500
And that resonates a lot more.

00:34:33.500 --> 00:34:36.800
So, what you have then is just interventions and cuttings, right?

00:34:36.940 --> 00:34:43.180
Like, without recourse to even a notion of convention as your justification.

00:34:43.860 --> 00:34:46.300
Or even a notion of what are you critiquing?

00:34:46.680 --> 00:34:47.620
Like, is there a serial?

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:49.000
Is there an Austin?

00:34:50.780 --> 00:34:52.080
Certainly not one, right?

00:34:52.160 --> 00:34:54.180
Like, I mean, certainly not, right?

00:34:54.320 --> 00:35:00.340
But, like, even a particular, I mean, it's easy to say that at the level of the subject, but is there even a line?

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:01.640
Right.

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:01.880
Right?

00:35:01.980 --> 00:35:02.200
Like.

00:35:02.500 --> 00:35:02.760
Yeah.

00:35:03.860 --> 00:35:10.920
I mean, because it really then forces you just to think, you know, none of this stuff pre-exists the configuration, right?

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:17.800
Like, it is the performance of the critique that produces an Austin or a serial to be critiqued.

00:35:17.860 --> 00:35:22.680
And the only question is, what kind of, what version of serial or Austin does it produce?

00:35:22.680 --> 00:35:23.120
That's right.

00:35:23.240 --> 00:35:24.240
That's where I love it.

00:35:24.240 --> 00:35:29.960
I mean, the refrain for me of these three lectures that I quoted, and this is paraphrasing it, but it's like,

00:35:29.960 --> 00:35:32.400
the theory of speech acts is made up of speech acts.

00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:33.560
Right?

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:40.520
Like, that's the thing that I feel like, you know, Searle doesn't think through, and most people don't, right?

00:35:40.620 --> 00:35:44.680
Like, that you're cutting even as you're describing what cutting is.

00:35:45.560 --> 00:35:45.700
Yeah.

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:46.780
Right.

00:35:46.900 --> 00:35:54.980
Well, I mean, just think about how much of the academy or just, like, the Western tradition of knowledge production writ large is,

00:35:54.980 --> 00:36:00.740
is that, like, the method, the tool, the observation has to be distanced from the object of study.

00:36:01.180 --> 00:36:06.940
And it gets really messy when the object of study becomes the method or the tool.

00:36:06.940 --> 00:36:07.680
It has to be.

00:36:07.680 --> 00:36:08.880
Like, it has to be.

00:36:09.220 --> 00:36:09.580
Right.

00:36:09.780 --> 00:36:16.060
And, you know, it's like every time, you know, even when I want to examine language or examine consciousness or examine myself,

00:36:16.140 --> 00:36:23.400
you know, there's always the performative move of distancing the examining version of myself from the examined version of myself.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:24.100
Right.

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:32.360
And you want to be able to believe the examining part of me isn't caught up in this chain of relationships, but it always, always is.

00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:38.460
And that's really, and it doesn't have to become the object of study to be caught up in those relationships.

00:36:39.620 --> 00:36:49.180
I guess that's an interesting way of saying it for me because I guess I feel like the anxiety that one feels at that idea is what, like,

00:36:50.620 --> 00:36:56.880
the feeling that you can't separate yourself, right, the feeling that you are at stake, right,

00:36:56.960 --> 00:37:07.140
the desire that fuels it, that fuels what produces that anxiety is, like, there's got to be a point, like, a subject removed from its object, right?

00:37:07.180 --> 00:37:16.060
There's just got to be, like, that sort of necessity of separating something out in order to look at it or to comment on it in some way.

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:25.060
And if they're both moving simultaneously, it's a feeling like there's, what, there's no point that I can rely on its stability.

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:30.660
And so when all of the points are moving at the same time, then you have a solar system, right?

00:37:30.820 --> 00:37:33.260
Like, you have actual life.

00:37:34.060 --> 00:37:36.140
But, so that's, okay, so that's interesting.

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:39.160
Like, consciousness is anti-life, right?

00:37:39.160 --> 00:37:39.340
Yeah.

00:37:39.340 --> 00:37:41.620
Like, it's an attempt to repudiate.

00:37:42.340 --> 00:37:45.020
That would make total sense within Nietzsche's economy.

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:45.900
Yeah.

00:37:46.480 --> 00:37:47.060
And to lose.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:48.400
Yeah.

00:37:48.640 --> 00:37:48.820
Yeah.

00:37:49.040 --> 00:37:49.540
For sure.

00:37:50.100 --> 00:37:56.320
By the way, it just occurred to me, we have talked about this at this, like, this is not going to make any sense to anyone.

00:37:56.460 --> 00:38:03.140
Like, this really might be the throwout podcast because I just don't think this is going to make any sense to anybody.

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:06.140
We've said that, this is interesting to me, very interesting.

00:38:06.140 --> 00:38:06.620
I agree.

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:09.240
Because we've said that, I think, about every Derrida episode.

00:38:09.720 --> 00:38:09.900
Yeah.

00:38:09.900 --> 00:38:10.480
Is it true?

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:14.660
And, you know, like, one of the, I think, it was maybe the Plato's Pharmacy one.

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:21.380
It's like, how do you, you know, we started with Hegel, which we all had, was all alien to us to a certain degree.

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:25.960
And, like, you know, a lot of the stuff that we've done, Heidegger was certainly alien to us to a certain degree.

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:29.740
And, you know, we focus on the text more then.

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:38.260
But every single Derrida one, it's like, there's a repulsor beam that prevents us from going to the text and thinking through it more, sort of like.

00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:39.140
Why is that?

00:38:39.140 --> 00:38:39.620
That's interesting.

00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:40.340
I think you're right.

00:38:40.620 --> 00:38:40.800
Yeah.

00:38:40.840 --> 00:38:47.240
And every single Derrida one, it's so, like, it's been a launching point for really great idiosyncratic conversation.

00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:48.180
I totally agree.

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:50.840
But it seems to be a symptom of intimacy.

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:51.420
Yeah.

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:51.940
Right.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:52.120
Yeah.

00:38:52.120 --> 00:38:55.480
We don't talk about the argument or the essay hardly at all, right?

00:38:55.500 --> 00:38:59.760
Like, it's like, we're like, okay, we presume that we all kind of understand the basic moves here.

00:38:59.780 --> 00:39:02.080
And now we're like, what are the implications of these moves?

00:39:02.100 --> 00:39:04.540
And how do we follow that somewhere else?

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:09.160
I just think for a listener to this, it's just not going to make any sense.

00:39:10.040 --> 00:39:10.220
Yeah.

00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:12.660
Well, I mean, it's a real question.

00:39:12.780 --> 00:39:16.540
Like, how do we proceed talking and thinking about and especially exposing?

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:22.740
And others to the thinkers that we're the most intimately connected with?

00:39:22.820 --> 00:39:27.480
Because, you know, what we could do is sort of like, we're going to detail it out and explain it to you.

00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:34.480
But I have a feeling that would feel more sterile than it would have with Hegel or anyone else.

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:35.340
Yeah.

00:39:35.460 --> 00:39:35.740
Yeah.

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:36.440
I don't know.

00:39:36.440 --> 00:39:41.340
I'm also like, I'm not sure any of our conversations have made any sense.

00:39:41.840 --> 00:39:50.020
Like, you know, like to a lay audience, I mean, what are you going to expect from, you have to have theory people listening to this.

00:39:50.260 --> 00:39:52.580
We have little sections where we're just shooting the shit.

00:39:53.020 --> 00:39:54.200
Anybody could listen to that.

00:39:54.200 --> 00:40:02.780
But once you get into the weeds with any of these thinkers, there's a select few who are going to be able to key in and be like, oh, yeah.

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:04.640
Like, and be able to follow our conversation.

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:06.240
So I don't, I don't think.

00:40:06.380 --> 00:40:09.440
But I just think, but in some of our episodes, that select few has been larger.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:11.640
And in other ones, they've been smaller.

00:40:11.820 --> 00:40:13.740
And I kind of agree with the Derrida ones.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.520
It might be an audience of three and we're all here.

00:40:17.140 --> 00:40:18.000
Right, right, right.

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:19.160
On one level, that's true.

00:40:19.220 --> 00:40:26.720
But on another level, like, what we're talking about, I mean, really, what we're talking about is the sort of everything being at play simultaneously.

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:30.300
Like, every concept, everything, every word, every, you know.

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:37.280
And that, to me, actually seems like a totally commonplace sort of problem, even if it's not theorized as such.

00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:44.120
Meaning, that's something that anyone who traffics at all in theory is, like, experiences, right?

00:40:44.260 --> 00:40:48.000
Like, that sort of, we're talking about as anxiety or whatever else.

00:40:48.420 --> 00:40:58.220
So, you know, to me, that's the point at which I feel like Derrida, Derrida's the one who shows you the extent to which everything is at play.

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:02.620
Like, the things that you thought, I mean, that's where I feel like the displacing of the grounds of logic.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:05.860
Displacing, not eradication, not erasure.

00:41:06.340 --> 00:41:17.380
But the displacing, in other words, showing you the movement through which, you know, the law of non-contradiction or whatever, like, is suspended, right?

00:41:17.520 --> 00:41:26.080
That, like, holding up this placard and being like, hey, there really is a solar system, and it's not a picture of, you know, a bunch of different planets.

00:41:26.080 --> 00:41:30.660
It's actually all orbiting all of the time, and that's what to live is.

00:41:31.240 --> 00:41:31.440
Right.

00:41:31.580 --> 00:41:31.880
You know?

00:41:32.320 --> 00:41:32.600
Right.

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:46.140
Yeah, I mean, and I don't know why I want to phrase it this way, but, like, could you, like, right, I mean, deconstruction is usually posed as, like, a critique of binaries or a critique of absolutes.

00:41:46.140 --> 00:42:00.260
But, I mean, could you say, this seems like such an undergrad comment, but could you say that context for Derrida, in this sort of radicalized sense, maybe you could call it contingency, that's, like, the one absolute?

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:06.840
Like, where you can't escape context or contingency in any final way.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:09.460
You can't make that cut between subject and object.

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:14.520
So, if Derrida were to entertain an absolute, it would have to be context.

00:42:14.940 --> 00:42:15.880
Well, I would say it this way.

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:19.100
You can make any cut, right?

00:42:19.180 --> 00:42:22.180
Like, you know, you can make the subject-object cut.

00:42:22.260 --> 00:42:23.220
It's just that it's a cut.

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:23.880
Yeah.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:24.240
Right?

00:42:24.360 --> 00:42:25.560
It's an intervention.

00:42:25.800 --> 00:42:26.540
It is an action.

00:42:26.960 --> 00:42:30.120
So, you know, you can, there are plenty of absolutes.

00:42:30.300 --> 00:42:32.100
It's not just that logic is displaced.

00:42:32.520 --> 00:42:33.940
It's multiplied as well.

00:42:34.080 --> 00:42:37.480
And we're making the subject-object cut one cut of many.

00:42:39.060 --> 00:42:39.500
Right.

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:42.500
But wouldn't the subject-object would be a provisional cut?

00:42:42.620 --> 00:42:43.600
Wouldn't it be for Derrida?

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:44.380
Everything is a provisional cut.

00:42:44.380 --> 00:42:44.960
Everything would be provisional cut.

00:42:44.960 --> 00:42:47.600
Everything is provisional and absolute?

00:42:48.460 --> 00:42:48.720
Yes.

00:42:48.900 --> 00:42:49.640
No, that's right.

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:52.220
Like, in that sense, like, or I would say it this way.

00:42:52.520 --> 00:42:55.860
What the absolute is, is a particular style of provisional cut.

00:42:56.340 --> 00:42:56.520
Yeah.

00:42:56.820 --> 00:42:59.180
So, one can cut provisionally and call it provisional,

00:42:59.260 --> 00:43:01.820
and one can cut provisionally and call it absolute, right?

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:04.800
Which we, by the way, we've had this conversation over and over again,

00:43:04.820 --> 00:43:07.340
because what that means from a Derridian, Delusian perspective

00:43:07.340 --> 00:43:09.980
is very different than what it means from a Hegelian perspective,

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:12.940
because, you know, like, imagining the flat playing of imminence,

00:43:12.940 --> 00:43:17.600
you know, Delus would say, like, yeah, people cut as if they're absolutes all the time,

00:43:17.620 --> 00:43:20.740
and those cuttings have very particular styles,

00:43:20.880 --> 00:43:22.180
very particular ramifications,

00:43:22.940 --> 00:43:32.460
but they're never able to transcend the ontological plane, right?

00:43:32.580 --> 00:43:33.980
They don't do what they think they're doing,

00:43:34.060 --> 00:43:35.820
but, you know what, basically nothing does,

00:43:35.920 --> 00:43:39.000
so that doesn't make them any better or worse than anything else.

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:41.720
I'm thinking about this from the perspective of,

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:43.700
I mean, I'm trying to think about how to make it more applicable

00:43:43.700 --> 00:43:51.240
outside of the sort of, like, the discourse on speech act theory,

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:54.860
and just think about it in terms of law, writ generally,

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:59.260
like, not even, you know, the, like, in the realm of, like, the natural law.

00:44:00.660 --> 00:44:08.860
And the impulse, you know, again, I think of a very, like, an impulse very much so rooted in anxiety.

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:11.520
People say, all right, well, if God's not running the show,

00:44:11.640 --> 00:44:14.360
there are laws that transcend physical interactions,

00:44:14.360 --> 00:44:20.260
and, you know, we can use science to sort of discover them and enumerate them

00:44:20.260 --> 00:44:22.420
and figure out the qualities of them.

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:28.960
And so that means that any interaction between any two physical bodies, right,

00:44:29.020 --> 00:44:33.640
is governed by a transcendent law that says these are the things that you can do,

00:44:33.700 --> 00:44:35.800
these are the things that you cannot do.

00:44:37.220 --> 00:44:42.140
And, like, what it would be to flatten law,

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:46.140
which we just think is essentially, constitutively transcendent.

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:51.020
What would, like, law changes in a pretty fundamental way

00:44:51.020 --> 00:44:55.420
when we think about it as imminent to everything else, right?

00:44:55.660 --> 00:44:55.980
Yes.

00:44:56.620 --> 00:44:57.700
Kafka's before the law.

00:44:58.380 --> 00:44:58.640
Yeah.

00:44:59.120 --> 00:44:59.300
Right.

00:44:59.420 --> 00:45:01.660
One's standing face-to-face with the doorkeeper.

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:05.480
One just imagines that there's a storyline of future doorkeepers.

00:45:06.080 --> 00:45:06.260
Yeah.

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:06.640
Yeah.

00:45:07.680 --> 00:45:11.180
And by, so, like, I mean, so there are two things operative here.

00:45:11.180 --> 00:45:14.660
One for all of the things supposedly governed by law,

00:45:14.740 --> 00:45:18.260
and then for law itself, that, you know, on the one hand,

00:45:19.040 --> 00:45:22.720
there is no transcendent law.

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:28.220
There are only the particular effects of forces working on each other, right?

00:45:29.200 --> 00:45:33.860
And then, two, one of those forces moves in a style that we call law.

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:35.340
Yeah.

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:38.660
And that is...

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:40.660
Well, it moves in a style that projects,

00:45:41.460 --> 00:45:43.840
retroactively projects a sense of transcendence.

00:45:43.980 --> 00:45:44.180
Yeah.

00:45:44.260 --> 00:45:45.820
A sense of transcendence.

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:46.220
Right.

00:45:46.300 --> 00:45:49.840
But the important point would be transcendence doesn't preexist.

00:45:50.600 --> 00:45:53.860
Transcendence is retroactively posited as preexistent.

00:45:53.900 --> 00:45:55.360
Again, Lacan on the real, right?

00:45:55.440 --> 00:45:56.680
Like, I mean, we've got many versions of that.

00:45:56.680 --> 00:46:01.280
Build a sense of transcendence on the, yeah, on the flat plane.

00:46:01.900 --> 00:46:02.560
Right, right.

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:08.200
So, yes, I mean, it's, it's, so, yeah, the, that sense of law is the same as saying

00:46:08.200 --> 00:46:10.360
speech act theory is a series of speech acts.

00:46:10.560 --> 00:46:10.940
Yeah.

00:46:11.060 --> 00:46:19.040
You know, that you are performatively constituting or cutting or elocutionarily cutting even

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:20.440
the elocutionary, right?

00:46:20.520 --> 00:46:25.420
Like, and, and, and that notion, I mean, it's like, it's, it's a question of regularities.

00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:30.660
It's like, look, gravity seems to be a fucking concept that plays out in, in a vast majority

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:32.680
of cases, except black holes and event horizons, right?

00:46:32.720 --> 00:46:36.720
Like, I mean, you know, so there's always these exceptions and you say, well, it's a law,

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:40.560
but it's a law, like every law has exceptions in, in that sense.

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:46.060
And you say, for these types of bodies, these things seem to regularly work this way in conjunction

00:46:46.060 --> 00:46:46.740
with one another.

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:48.720
But that's just like a matter of frequency.

00:46:48.720 --> 00:46:52.820
It's like, yeah, you know, when I tune my radio into the right station, then I get that

00:46:52.820 --> 00:46:56.200
broadcast, but I get outside of those parameters and it's something else.

00:46:56.200 --> 00:47:02.460
And you know, like, I mean, there is such like a, a, a privileging of, you know, the, a human

00:47:02.460 --> 00:47:07.300
point of origin because you think, well, you know, when things get really, really big, then

00:47:07.300 --> 00:47:09.100
the laws of gravity change.

00:47:09.180 --> 00:47:10.900
When things get really, really fast, they change.

00:47:10.940 --> 00:47:12.560
When they get really, really slow, they change.

00:47:12.640 --> 00:47:14.480
When they get really, really small, they change.

00:47:14.520 --> 00:47:19.080
And then you realize, wait a second, really, really big compared to what?

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:20.760
Really, really small compared to what?

00:47:21.100 --> 00:47:21.700
Us, right?

00:47:21.700 --> 00:47:27.600
Like, cause you have to realize there's an infinite, you know, like scope of bigger from

00:47:27.600 --> 00:47:31.800
that, that, that takes what we take as really, really big as a starting point.

00:47:31.800 --> 00:47:35.480
And then there's an infinite scope of really, like, smaller from that takes what we take as

00:47:35.480 --> 00:47:37.240
really, really small as a starting point.

00:47:37.240 --> 00:47:39.320
So you just started talking about space and you freaked me out.

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:39.540
I know, I know, I know.

00:47:39.540 --> 00:47:41.280
Have we gone through my aversion to space?

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:41.600
I know.

00:47:43.080 --> 00:47:44.680
But it is, it is the problem.

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:47.000
It is the same anxiety question that we're talking about.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:47.180
Yeah.

00:47:47.180 --> 00:47:49.500
Like, it's, yeah, I can't think about that.

00:47:49.640 --> 00:47:52.560
I can only think about it as a model, as a static model.

00:47:52.960 --> 00:47:57.960
But we think about, like, our experience as an infinite array, right?

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:03.040
Like, we're, we're in the middle and then there's infinite in one direction and there's

00:48:03.040 --> 00:48:04.380
infinite in another direction.

00:48:04.580 --> 00:48:11.040
And then if you're going to take infinity seriously, you have to realize that that scope,

00:48:11.040 --> 00:48:17.780
that band of infinity is infinitesimally small compared to, like, forget about there are

00:48:17.780 --> 00:48:19.040
exceptions to gravity.

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:24.600
The vast majority of probably existence is an exception to what we take to be the norm

00:48:24.600 --> 00:48:25.280
of gravity.

